  "prompt": "What is \"Midwest\"?",
  "response": "The term \"Midwest\" refers to a region in the United States that is generally considered to be in the north-central part of the country. The exact boundaries of the Midwest can vary depending on the context, but it typically includes the following states:\n\n- Illinois\n- Indiana\n- Iowa\n- Kansas\n- Michigan\n- Minnesota\n- Missouri\n- Nebraska\n- North Dakota\n- Ohio\n- South Dakota\n- Wisconsin\n\nSometimes, parts of other states, such as Kentucky or Oklahoma, may also be included in the Midwest depending on the definition used.\n\nThe Midwest is known for its diverse geography, which includes expansive plains, the Great Lakes, and significant agricultural areas. It is often referred to as \"America's Heartland\" due to its central location and its historical and cultural significance in the development of the United States.\n\nThe region is characterized by a mix of urban and rural areas, with major cities such as Chicago, Detroit, Minneapolis, and St. Louis playing important roles in the economy and culture. The Midwest is also known for its strong industrial base, particularly in manufacturing, as well as its agricultural output, producing a significant portion of the nation's corn, soybeans, and livestock.",
